      <div set:html={`<h2 id="how-to-send-epub-to-kindle">How to Send EPUB to Kindle: Email, USB &amp; App Guide (2026)</h2>

<p>If you own a Kindle and have an EPUB file you want to read on it, you've probably run into Amazon's wall: Kindles don't natively open <code>.epub</code> files. You see "Send to Kindle" in the menus, but the file disappears or the device says "Unsupported Format."</p>

<p>You <strong>can</strong> send EPUBs to a Kindle — it just takes the right method. In 2026, Amazon's Send to Kindle service auto-converts EPUB to the Kindle's native format behind the scenes, so you don't need to manually convert EPUB to MOBI first. But not every method handles EPUB the same way, and there are quirks you should know.</p>

<p>This guide covers all three ways to get an EPUB onto your Kindle — email, USB, and the Kindle app — plus troubleshooting tips for each.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="method-1-send-to-kindle-by-email">Method 1: Send to Kindle by Email</h2>

<p>The email method is the most reliable way to get EPUB files on a Kindle. Amazon runs each file through its own conversion pipeline, and it handles EPUB, PDF, DOCX, and even TXT attachments.</p>

<h3>Step 1: Find your Send to Kindle email address</h3>
<p>Amazon assigns each Kindle device its own @kindle.com email address. To find yours:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Amazon.com &gt; Account &gt; Manage Your Content and Devices</strong></li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Devices</strong> tab</li>
  <li>Find your Kindle in the list and click <strong>Actions &gt; Manage device</strong></li>
  <li>Your Send to Kindle email is listed as <code>yourname_kindle.com</code> (it will look like <code>jdoe_123@kindle.com</code>)</li>
</ol>

<h3>Step 2: Approve your email address</h3>
<p>Amazon only accepts emails from approved senders. If you use Gmail, Proton, or work email, you must add it to the approved list first:</p>
<ol>
  <li>On the same content management page, click the <strong>Preferences</strong> tab</li>
  <li>Scroll to <strong>Personal Document Settings</strong></li>
  <li>Add your email address under <strong>Approved Personal Document Email List</strong></li>
</ol>

<h3>Step 3: Send the EPUB as an attachment</h3>
<p>Compose a new email, attach your EPUB file, and send it to your Kindle's @kindle.com address. The subject line and body can be blank — Amazon ignores them.</p>
<p>Amazon will process the file and deliver it over Wi-Fi within 1-5 minutes. If you see the book appear but with a generic title like "Sent to Kindle" document, Amazon's metadata extraction didn't pick up your EPUB's internal title — a small annoyance we'll cover in the FAQ.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="method-2-usb-transfer-with-calibre">Method 2: USB Transfer with Calibre</h2>

<p>For large libraries (100+ books), readers who travel without reliable Wi-Fi, or EPUBs with custom formatting that Amazon's email pipeline mangles, USB transfer is the better option.</p>

<p>Calibre is the go-to tool. It's free, open-source, and acts as a full library manager that converts and syncs to any ereader.</p>

<h3>Connect and transfer</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Connect your Kindle to your computer via USB</li>
  <li>Open Calibre — it should auto-detect the Kindle and show it as a device icon in the toolbar</li>
  <li>Select the EPUB in your Calibre library, or drag a new EPUB into the library</li>
  <li>Calibre will ask if you want to convert EPUB to the Kindle's preferred format (now AZW3 or KFX) — click <strong>Yes</strong> to get better formatting than the raw EPUB</li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Send to Device</strong> button</li>
</ol>

<p>One tip: Calibre's built-in conversion pipeline (EPUB → AZW3) often produces better results than Amazon's email-based conversion, especially for EPUBs with custom fonts, embedded CSS, or complex tables.</p>

<h3>KFX support</h3>
<p>Newer Kindles (2024 and later) support the KFX format, which enables Amazon's enhanced typesetting features. Calibre 9.x includes a KFX Output plugin that converts EPUB directly to KFX, preserving drop caps, sidebars, and publisher fonts better than AZW3.</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="method-3-kindle-app-desktop-and-mobile">Method 3: Kindle App (Desktop and Mobile)</h2>

<p>The Kindle app on iOS, Android, Mac, and Windows doesn't directly open EPUB files either — but you can use a workaround with cloud sync.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Amazon.com/sendtokindle</strong> in your browser (this is Amazon's web uploader, not email)</li>
  <li>Drag and drop your EPUB file onto the upload area</li>
  <li>Choose which device(s) to deliver to — including any Kindle app you have installed</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Upload</strong></li>
</ol>

<p>The file appears in your Kindle library on all synced apps within a minute. This method works well as a wirelessly-to-phone option when you're away from your computer.</p>

<hr />

